div.div: What's missing from this analysis is a meta-analysis of weight paths.
- Why are weight paths sometimes equivalent? (similar feature importance, corrupt data, coincidence, etc)

- What does it mean for weight paths to be equivalent? (the illusion of similarity/alignment or a genuine symmetry may be generating the similarity in feature importance in the system, like how corners in an object can generate similar change patterns between different sub-objects)
- What are the core weight paths in the system, and what do they mean? (what is the normally distributed weight path in the system, what are the core distortion functions between weight paths)
The core weight paths in the system should be those that can be used to calculate the other weight paths given core distortion functions of weight paths.

If there's a normal or otherwise standard weight path that explains variance of the type found in the data set or between the features, that should be identified once the model is done training, and the trajectory followed during testing to make sure that weight path is followed by the test data - otherwise the test data may be non-normally distributed.
- Which weight path patterns can be generated with which data set variable type/metadata/variation/relationships
and which network parameters?
- Which weight path patterns are associated with the target level of certainty in the prediction?
- Which weight path patterns would allow the level of variation likely to be present in input variables, even if that variation is not in the data set?
- Which weight path patterns would allow the change patterns normally seen in variables of this type & variable sets like this?

- Which weight path patterns allow for more variable relationships, and are those a hub in the network of weight path patterns? (allowing for different causal shapes like loops & networks rather than just a one-directional causal tree)

- What is the significance of weight path patterns with regard to the problem type? Do some weight path patterns map to type differences in a network designed for classification? Are weight path patterns an indicator of a range of prediction functions approaching the final function, with different sets of data of varying quality?

- Do weight path patterns gravitate around different core prediction functions for the variables in the data set based on variable metadata/relationships? (core prediction functions meaning the best loss-minimizer function, the best generalized function, the best change-handling function, the best future-state prediction function, and other function metadata, and core distortion functions including the transforms between these standard prediction function metadata)

- Do weight path patterns reveal information that isn't handled by normal prediction methods, like how a particular prediction function is likely to fail given its deviation from core prediction functions)
- Do weight path patterns reveal information about assumptions (differences assumed to follow expected patterns in training/test/prod data) or the problem type (convergence patterns of types)

- Can you skip training in some circumstances and just generate the weight path patterns that are the most different paths that could be explanatory of the data set, to capture likely different important states of the variable set, and then test your data on those patterns to find out which weight path set includes the best predictors?

div.b: Using Difference Patterns to generate Prediction Function
(or prediction metadata, like range of weight path patterns)

div.div: The points of greatest difference are important in determining prediction functions. This includes the points of greatest difference in weight path patterns & common core prediction functions for this variable set metadata.
Some network algorithms & parameters may not be capable of generating the weight path patterns for certain problem types.

You would use weight path patterns to resolve which one is the best predictor, beyond using core distortion functions of common core prediction functions given the data set, which might only reduce your problem to resolving which weight path pattern set includes the best predictors.

For example, if your data set has two identifiable clusters (with enough overlap or points in between to require a prediction function), there are many types of functions that could fit this data, but you may be able to use prediction patterns to reduce the solution space of possible functions to certain function types or even ranges of function metadata within a function type.

If weight path patterns are normally distributed around a mean for a variable set type, then the weight path patterns used to initialize the neural network to test if you can skip training would be distortions around the average & the standard deviations.

Example of a variable set type: one direct causative variable (tail), two foundation variables (mutation count in DNA sample, health conditions of animal), a type variable (sub-species relationship to origin species type), an emergent & learned variable (behavior like barking)

Another use case for this data is using neural networks to determine the best core prediction functions, the best core distortion functions of prediction functions, the best weight path parameters, etc for a given variable set type or other variable set metadata, and re-using those insights for problems of that type (classification, classification with insufficient data variance, classification with changing classes, etc).

The best filters to apply when reducing a variable set type to a target variable type can be generated as a trajectory between this function, variable, and distribution metadata. A trajectory navigating from a core prediction function to the probable causal shapes of the variable set to the core distortion functions to the core weight paths for a given variable set might produce sequential filters like:

- apply common distortion patterns across weight path distortion functions, prediction function distortion functions, and variable distortion functions in variable subset relationships first (including patterns from prediction functions & weight paths because weight path patterns might have different bias than prediction function patterns)
- start with the bias of commonness/average when selecting starting functions, and apply distortions based on commonness/average
- bias patterns are key to integrate as well, given the bias toward equivalence (randomness) and normality (average) present in natural phenomena and analysis of that phenomena.

div.b: Applying Causal Shape in the Prediction Problem Space

div.div: Relationship types from different causal shapes can be applied to relate variables or explain change in a variable: the causal network can explain the relationships from a hub or root variable that generates other variables, or it can explain a variable with different versions of itself. A causal set can capture type relationships but so can the other shapes - which one is best depends on available information about the type metadata & the data set variation.
If multiple variables have different versions, it might be worthwhile to display the adjacent probable prediction functions as combinations of these versions.
Common variable distortion patterns can also generate this relationship (variables commonly change over time, in a network pattern).

div.div: This core function & metadata analysis can be used to derive other important metadata, like patterns of change, prediction patterns, relationship patterns, attribute patterns, and semantic metadata like concepts & intent.
It's important to know the reason why a function is a clear distortion of another or a combination of several functions:
- is it because efficiency or commonness is prioritized in this type of phenomena?

- is it because the variable involved were metrics of agent interactions, and those agents had varying levels of agency, where one agent was able to make calculations about the value added by cooperation and one agent was not
- are change patterns like intersection, convergence, combination, sequence, cooperation, alignment, and distortion predictable for certain variable types or variable sets?

Answering questions about function metadata, adjacent functions, and relationships to related function objects like bias & variables can help generate multiple probable solutions before applying other analysis types for solution resolution, and filter the solution space without over-dependence on data.
Then questions like 'what is the intent of this network parameter value, given this context' can be answered where previously their intent was too abstract to be calculated in isolation.
With this analysis, network parameters may have clear intents like:
- expand the set of weight paths explored
- start at a certain type of a set of weight paths (normal, common weight path patterns for this problem type, etc)
- explore a set of weight paths with x variance and y number of weights
- explore a set of weight paths with distortions generated by distortion functions a & b
- match the range of weight paths explored to the variance in the data set

div.b: Other key questions can be answered or have their solution space reduced:

div.div: - what problems are solved or created by this intent trajectory/combination
- what intents can neutralize this intent trajectory
- what causal shapes can we expect if this intent combination is allowed to continue without interference
- what type changes are causative & imminent given this intent combination
- what is the next generation of this prediction function likely to be
- what new distortion functions are evolving, given this prediction function & intent trajectory
- given these combinations of related variables, what new or alternate core prediction function could we have started from that would have reduced learning time
- is there an optimal set of core prediction functions to start from for most problems

div.div: To apply this pattern, we can use the example of a relationship that seems absurd/unlikely or even impossible using the common limits like commonness & average, but which ends up being either explanatory or a more efficient route to the actual function than the simpler composition of core distortion functions.

The less likely distortion functions have an advantage in that they can reveal errors in assumptions that built the core function set, or changing relationships that invalidate the previous core function set. Ideally both methods would be applied at regular intervals to update a prediction function.

A good example is the occasional conspiracy that's true. A change in demand for a product could be people having a better alternative (simple core distortion function from the market problem space), but it could also be a conspiracy from a big industry lobbying group to ice out the competition because they had insider information that the producers of that good were using profits to invest in research in a product that could invalidate their revenue streams (complex function built by multiple unlikely distortion functions).
The random function is a structural/conceptual core function across-systems, so a simple relationship could use that to explain the trajectory from A to B.
Core market functions would produce a better explanatory trajectory between A & B, which is nearer to the actual function shape.

Applying more market distortion functions (whether new product is actually better & on which metrics, whether utility is improved, whether marketing was used to make the new product seem better, whether the previous & new product even fulfill the same demand structure) can improve this trajectory.

The absurd/unlikely trajectory could be framed as a joke, that's how silly it is "I bet the reason people are buying more soy products than corn is because there's a secret conspiracy to turn us all into Soy Boys". But even though it's silly, it's not only within the range of possibility, but agents in the market problem space have incentives & tools to not only make that happen, but to market it as something else like genuine shift in demand, hiding their intents completely.
